commit.message: Use MongoDB to store access tokens, be much less stateful, fix #8
Landing page
Update README.md

remove github_finish endpoint and refactor default repo name

The default name for the gitmail repository is "gitmail". Rather than
bake this string into the construction of the GithubConf value, this
default name is now exposed as a top-level binding in the Types module.
add minor docs to Time module

implement redis listener thread and rework auth token storage

We used to just store the access token, but that doesn't work because we
need the username. Furthermore, the oauth web flow doesn't even give us
the username! In order to get it we need to make an API call that is not
supported in any version of the library lower than 0.14, which we depend
on as of a previous commit.

Now, upon completion of the oauth flow, we make the API call to query
the authenticated user's data and store a GithubConf, (serialized to
JSON,) which contains the username, the bearer token, and the gitmail
repo name, to Redis.

In a future revision, we should store this information in a database.

bump up required github library version

This version is bleeding edge and not on hackage yet.

add trivial deployment script

It just runs cabal run.
switch to port 8000 for github service

implement github oauth web flow

* Visiting /github_start will commence the oauth web flow.
* Security precautions against CSRF are taken by storing nonces in
    redis.
* There is currently no database support, so access tokens are simply
    stored in redis. There's equally no support for multiple users; only
    the last authorized user's access token is stored, with the
    hard-coded key "access_token".
